  "text": "We have been investigating a simpler assay method for identifying intestinal bacterial species by bacterial nucleic acid hybridization. As a first step of our study, we describe here the usefulness of a bacterial DNA hybridization assay for identifying intestinal Bacteroides species. Some Bacteroides species are thought to play a role in inducing colon cancer through production of fecapentaenes, mutagens found in human feces [CITATION_1] . Our final goal is to investigate the possibility of identifying persons that are at high risk for colorectal neoplasia on the basis of their fecal bacterial profile and are thus suitable targets for cancer screening and other preventive measures.",
